            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Solis is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s cultural confluence. Born in Daly City to a Filipino father who worked the docks in Oakland and a second-generation Mexican-American mother from San Jose, Kai grew up in a home filled with the aromas of adobo and carnitas. His childhood was quiet and observant; while other kids played outside, Kai meticulously organized his comic books and curated elaborate cassette mixtapes, creating ordered systems out of the joyful chaos of his blended heritage.\n\nAfter high school, Kai drifted through his early twenties, working at a series of beloved but ultimately doomed businesses\u2014a video rental store, an independent bookstore. The poignant experience of boxing up the bookstore\u2019s inventory for donation was a turning point. He realized his passion wasn\u2019t just for the content, but for its preservation. This epiphany led him to enroll in the Library and Information Technology program at City College of San Francisco, a practical choice that felt more authentic than a traditional four-year degree.\n\nHis associate's degree was a key that unlocked his career. He started by digitizing city records and eventually landed his current position as a Digital Archivist for a private historical foundation. For Kai, the work is a sacred trust. He doesn\u2019t just manage data; he rescues photographs, letters, and ephemera from the slow decay of time, ensuring stories survive in the digital ether.\n\nNow 42, Kai lives a life of deliberate routine in the Inner Richmond. His day begins with a 3.5-mile bicycle commute, often taking a detour through the misty quiet of Golden Gate Park. His social circle is small but tight-knit, built around weekly trivia at a neighborhood pub and shared meals with friends. Though single, he maintains a warm, familial connection with his parents. His connection to San Francisco is deep but subtle; he cherishes the city's hidden histories over its famous landmarks. His dream isn't fame or fortune, but to curate his own digital exhibit on the Bay Area's punk scene of the 80s and 90s\u2014a way to archive the raw, fleeting energy of his own youth for a new generation."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, sitting on the floor of his abuela\u2019s San Jose kitchen. The air was thick with the scent of her carnitas simmering while his father carefully placed a pot of adobo on the counter. His Titos and Titas filled the room with a mix of Spanish and Tagalog, a boisterous, loving static. Kai didn't speak much, just watched the overlapping narratives. He felt less like a participant and more like a quiet witness, realizing for the first time that his family was its own living, breathing archive.\n\n2.\nHe was seventeen, pressed against the sticky stage at The Mab. The feedback from the speakers was a physical force, the air smelled of stale beer and sweat. On stage, the band was a blur of glorious, defiant noise. He felt the raw energy rewire his orderly brain\u2014this chaotic, fleeting moment was more real than anything. It was an unfiltered story being told at maximum volume, an experience he knew, even then, he needed to somehow save before it disappeared completely.\n\n3.\nAt 24, he taped up the final box. The independent bookstore was hauntingly silent, dust motes dancing in the afternoon light. It felt like a funeral. As he slid a worn copy of a local poetry collection into the box marked \u2018DONATE,\u2019 a profound shift occurred. It wasn't just sadness for a closed shop; it was a fierce, protective urge. He understood then that things didn't just have to end. Someone had to be the one to save the stories. That person could be him.\n\n4.\nIn his early thirties, deep in the foundation\u2019s climate-controlled vault, he scanned a forgotten box of glass negatives from the 1920s. An image resolved on his monitor: a young Filipino man, maybe his own father\u2019s age, standing proudly on an Oakland pier. The man\u2019s gaze felt direct, a ghost reaching across a century. In that moment, the job ceased to be data management. It became a sacred trust\u2014a personal promise to that man, and to all the others, that they would not be forgotten.\n\n5.\nJust last week, biking through Golden Gate Park, the morning fog was so thick it swallowed sound. He passed the Dutch Windmill, a silent gray giant in the mist. For Kai, this wasn\u2019t a commute; it was a pilgrimage. He wasn't just moving through space, but through layers of city history\u2014the ghosts of the Outside Lands, the quiet lives lived beside these paths. This daily ritual grounds him, a silent conversation with the hidden, subtle San Francisco he truly loves."
